<Document>
<name>Overseas Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Overseas Highway</h2><p><i>Florida, USA · US-1, Florida City to Key West</i></p><p><b>182 km across 42 bridges and 800+ islands — the road that goes to sea.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>192 km (119 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs without stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–May (avoid hurricane season Jun–Nov, peak intensity Aug–Oct)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Drunk drivers (especially Sunday afternoons); pedestrian fishermen on bridges; iguanas; one-lane traffic during repaving</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>217</td></tr></table><hr><p>Henry Flagler's Overseas Railroad, 'the railroad that went to sea,' opened in 1912 and was destroyed by the 1935 Labor Day hurricane — still the most intense landfall ever recorded in the United States. The state of Florida turned the surviving bridges into the highway you drive today. 42 bridges, 113 miles, 800-some islands. The Seven-Mile Bridge is the longest stretch of road over open water you will ever cross. Mile markers count down from MM 113 (Florida City) to MM 0 (Key West). Drive south, return north — your lane on the way back faces the sunset.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>John Pennekamp Coral Reef SP</b> — First underwater state park in the US (1963). Glass-bottom boat tours and snorkel trips to the only living coral reef in the continental US.</li><li><b>Robbie's Marina (Islamorada)</b> — Hand-feed enormous tarpon (nearly 2 m) at the dock — pelicans crash the line. Iconic Keys experience for $5.</li><li><b>Pigeon Key</b> — Walkable historic island — original construction camp for Flagler's railroad. Small museum; reach by tram or walk on the old bridge.</li><li><b>Bahia Honda State Park</b> — Arguably the best beach in the Keys: turquoise water, good shade, snorkeling from shore. Old railroad bridge segment is photogenic.</li><li><b>National Key Deer Refuge</b> — Endemic miniature deer (about the size of a Labrador) — descended from white-tails marooned by sea-level rise after the last Ice Age. Approach No Name Key at dawn.</li><li><b>Southernmost Point buoy</b> — Touristy painted concrete buoy in Key West. 90 mi (145 km) to Cuba. Photo-line reliably long.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
